hands_on_practices.solution:
Let $r=\sqrt{b^{2}+c^{2}}$. Since $b^{2}+c^{2}\neq 0$, we have $r0$.

First Givens rotation $G_{1}$ acts on the $(y,z)$-plane (indices $2,3$) and is chosen so that it maps $[b,c]^{T}$ to $[r,0]^{T}$ with nonnegative second component. Using the standard Givens construction, choose
$$\cos\theta_{1}=\frac{b}{r},\qquad \sin\theta_{1}=-\frac{c}{r}.$$
Thus
$$
G_{1}=\begin{pmatrix}
1  0  0\\
0  \frac{b}{r}  \frac{c}{r}\\
0  -\frac{c}{r}  \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix},
\qquad
G_{1}\begin{pmatrix}a\\ b\\ c\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a \\
\frac{b^{2}+c^{2}}{r} \\
0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a\\ r\\ 0
\end{pmatrix}
\equiv \mathbf{v}'.
$$

Second Givens rotation $G_{2}$ acts on the $(x,y)$-plane (indices $1,2$) and is chosen so that it maps $[a,r]^{T}$ to $[1,0]^{T}$. Since $a^{2}+r^{2}=1$, we set
$$\cos\theta_{2}=a,\qquad \sin\theta_{2}=-r,$$
giving
$$
G_{2}=\begin{pmatrix}
a  r  0\\
-r  a  0\\
0  0  1
\end{pmatrix},
\qquad
G_{2}\mathbf{v}'=
\begin{pmatrix}
a  r  0\\
-r  a  0\\
0  0  1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
a\\ r\\ 0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1\\ 0\\ 0
\end{pmatrix}
=\mathbf{e}_{1}.
$$

Therefore, the composite rotation is $R=G_{2}G_{1}$. Multiplying,
$$
R
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a  r  0\\
-r  a  0\\
0  0  1
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
1  0  0\\
0  \frac{b}{r}  \frac{c}{r}\\
0  -\frac{c}{r}  \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a  b  c\\
-r  \frac{ab}{r}  \frac{ac}{r}\\
0  -\frac{c}{r}  \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
A direct check shows $R\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{e}_{1}$ since
$$
\begin{pmatrix}
a  b  c\\
-r  \frac{ab}{r}  \frac{ac}{r}\\
0  -\frac{c}{r}  \frac{b}{r}
\end{pmatrix}
\begin{pmatrix}
a\\ 
b\\ 
c
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
a^{2}+b^{2}+c^{2}\\ 
-ar+\frac{a(b^{2}+c^{2})}{r}\\ 
0
\end{pmatrix}
=
\begin{pmatrix}
1\\ 
0\\ 
0
\end{pmatrix}.
$$
Thus, with $r=\sqrt{b^{2}+c^{2}}$, the desired composite rotation matrix is as above.
